      <hedline>
        <hl1>When Politics Clashes With Science</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rebecca L Orris letter on Republican strategist Frank Luntz's advice on handling global warming issue; points out that majority of government-funded scientists strongly support evidence that global warming is occurring, and politicians and the public should accept that judgment (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Call for Softer, Greener Language'' (news article, March 2):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Call for Softer, Greener Language'' (news article, March 2):</p>
        <p>The advice of Frank Luntz, a Republican strategist, to the G.O.P. that winning the global warming debate requires Republicans to ''be even more active in recruiting experts who are sympathetic to your view'' is all wrong.</p>
        <p>Government financing supports most of the research being done on climate change. The majority of scientists strongly support the evidence that global warming is occurring as a result of the increasing levels of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.</p>
        <p>It is the responsibility of politicians and the public to allow the scientists to make this judgment.</p>
        <p>It is O.K. for a politician to say, ''The evidence says global warming is occurring, but we can't afford to do anything at this time.'' It is not O.K. for a politician to deny that there is sufficient evidence to say it will occur.</p>
        <p>Otherwise, why finance scientific research?</p>
        <p>REBECCA L. ORRIS  Kensington, Md., March 2, 2003</p>
      </block>
